@node Introduction "Magic Colors, what does it actually do?"

                         @{b}Introduction to Magic Colors@{ub}

Have you ever heard of WBVerlauf?  It is an AGA program which creates wonderful color slides on screen background. I don't know yet if there's a version of WBVerlauf or any similar program for OCS/ECS chipset, but I just decided to write my own anyway (I just like using self-made programs:). Take a look at the @{"features" link Features} of Magic Colors.

You can define the color at the top of the screen and the color at the bottom of the screen.  Magic Colors then creates a color slide between these two colors (from the top to the bottom of the screen) using 2-16 steps between. You can believe it looks great, especially if you know which colors look smooth together. Look at the restrictions on OCS/ECS palette at @{"Technical Information" link TechnicalInformation} and @{"Future plans" link Future}.
@endnode

@node Features "Magic Colors - programmed in two days"

                      @{b}Features provided by Magic Colors@{ub}

· Fully system friendly

· Commodities interface

· Wonderful looking GUI

· You can edit, load & save your own slides
· Ten more or less good-looking slides in @{"Presets menu" link Menus}

· If you don't like this program, you can quit it by
	· pressing the @{"Quit button" link Buttons}
	· choosing the @{"Quit menu item" link Menus} in the Project menu
	· killing Magic Colors in C= Exchange program
	· signalling CTRL-C
	· :-)

· And it even@{b} does @{ub}the copper color slide on background as promised! Impressed enough, eh? Then take a look at the @{"system requirements" link SystemRequirements} !
@endnode

@node SystemRequirements "Magic Color - never available for PCs!"

At first you'll need a machine. In this particular case, this certain machine should be a so called computer, more precisely an@{b} Amiga @{ub}compatible number cruncher. This means Magic Colors isn't (and won't be) available for your lawnmover, harvester, truck or elevator.

Even if you own an Amiga computer you might not have Kickstart 2.0 or newer. Then shame and go buy a brand new Kickstart or even a brand new Amiga! But we all do have KS2.0+, don't we? Good. Another requirement is memory: Magic Colors will eat couple of kilobytes of memory, which actually is quite a lot for this kind of program. Please forgive me, it's because of my gadget creation library which is about 20 kilobytes in size. Perhaps I should make a shared library of it?

If you have a computer described above you should be ready to @{"get started" link GettingStarted}.
@endnode

@node GettingStarted "Make a program a fool can use and only fools will use it"

@{b}Installing Magic Colors@{ub}

The installation couldn't actually be much more easier: drag the Magic Colors icon to your@{b} SYS:WBStartup @{ub}drawer and run it. It should @{"popup" link Commodities} by default so you'll see the control window of Magic Colors. Try choosing default slides from @{"Presets menu" link Menus} and store it by clicking the @{"Save" link Buttons} button. This stores your favorite default color slide to ENV: and ENVARC: so it will be loaded and used automatically next time you start Magic Colors. You might not want MagicColors to popup everytime you run it. You can disabled popping up with @{"CX_POPUP tooltype" link AdvancedOptions}.

Next, drag this@{b} MagicColors.guide @{ub} file wherever you store document files. This operation finishes the installation. If you're a guru, a hacker or otherwise familiar with @{b} Amigas @{ub} you have probably installed Magic Colors already before reading this documentation. I hope you had no@{b} RTFM @{ub}s.

Have a break, get a beer or just make some hot chocolate or tea (who could possibly drink @{b} coffee @{ub}?-) and enjoy your colorful screen for about five minutes. Then study the @{"buttons and menus" link ButtonsAndMenus}.
@endnode

@node ButtonsAndMenus "Dad, can I press this button?"

The Magic Colors control window contains @{"buttons" link Buttons} and @{"menus" link Menus}. Now you'll need to use some of your brain capabilities to choose which one you want to read about.

You might still be interested in @{"the author" link Author}, @{"distribution" link Distribution}, @{"all that law stuff" link Disclaimer}, @{"advanced options" link AdvancedOptions}, @{"technical information" link TechnicalInformation} or @{"future plans" link Future}.

@endnode

@node Buttons "Holy butts!"

@{b}Control window buttons:@{ub}

· Start group
	· Here you can set the color at the top
	  of the screen by using appropriate @{b}R@{ub},
	  @{b}G@{ub} and @{b}B@{ub} sliders

· End group
	· This works like the former group, but
	  affects the color at bottom of the
	  screen

· Colors slider
	Set the number of steps used in
	the color slide

· Commands group
	· Save button:	saves current color slide to
			@{b}ENV:@{ub} and @{b}ENVARC:@{ub}
	· Hide button:	hides the control window (same
			as pressing '@{b}Hide Window@{ub}' button
			in the @{b}Exchange@{ub} window
	· Quit button:	quits Magic Colors

· Standard 'Window Close Gadget'
	· This has the same function as @{b}Hide@{ub} button
@endnode

@node Menus "I'll take your menus away; bon appetit - enjoy your dinner!"

· Project menu
	· Open
		Opens a slide file

	· Save as
		Saves current slide as separate slide
		datafile.

	· About
		Displays a requester with general
		information on Magic Colors

	· Hide
		Does the same as @{"Hide" link Buttons} button

	· Save
		Does the same as @{"Save" link Buttons} button

· Presets menu
	· Ten precreated slides you can play with before you
	  start creating your own slides
@endnode

